You can&#39;t use an enhanced for loop (`for (String e: Variable)`) for your purpose.

From the contents of the loop (`Distance.get(Variable.indexOf(e))`) it seems that you want to access the `Distance` list at the same indices as the `Variable` list, but using the enhanced for loop and `Variable.indexOf(e)` doesn&#39;t allow you to do that - `Variable.indexOf(e)` always returns the **first** index where it finds `e` (&quot;VIB1 DISTANCE&quot;) (and it may even be unable to find `e` because it could have been &quot;vib1 distance&quot; and `indexOf()` does a case-sensitive comparison).

The solution is to use a classical indexed for loop:

         for (int i = 0; i &lt; Variable.size(); i++) {
             if (Variable.get(i).equalsIgnoreCase(&quot;VIB1 DISTANCE&quot;)) {
                 
                 double priorDistance = Distance.get(i-1);
                 double VibDistance = Distance.get(i);
                  
                 if ((VibDistance - priorDistance) &gt;= priorDistance) {
                     numberPositive++;
                 }
             }
         }

This might still have problems (what if the very first line contains &quot;VIB1 DISTANCE&quot;?) but will solve the first problem.

